This was delicious!! I was a bit timid on making this dish, since I've never actually made a prime rib-roast before. But it came out beautifully & I was throughly impressed. I followed the recipe as stated, but chopped everything finely instead of using a mortar-n-pestle. Don't have one of those & wasn't really wanting to purchase one. Personally, I think the roast came out just as well without the marinade having to be paste-like quality. I marinaded the roast for over 24hrs, mine was ~2-4lbs with 1-rib. Yes, it was smaller than what the recipe called for. But then I wasn't feeding an army. When I make this again, I shall have a roast b/w 2-3 ribs & watch more intently the cooking of it. This time, it was a bit overdone. Probably should have watched it a bit more, though it didn't matter much cause the only pieces left were attached the bone & that was delicious as well. YUM!! The only thing I question is the cooking at 450 F for 20min. During that time period, it smelled as if the roast was burning. I suppose if your oven is immaculately clean then cooking anything at 450 F wouldn't matter much. But for me, I have better things to do then to slave about cleaning my oven after each time I use it. It smelled as though the oven was burning the tar off the metal, rather than searing the roast. I think next time, I'll sear the roast on the stove-top before baking in the oven. Otherwise, very delicious!!

