Ok, didn't have time for the 8+ hours of marinade. Also, didn't have the fresh herbs & only had California Bay leaves ! Sounds like a great start for this recipe eh? From the many recipes I have cooked from Epicurious I know you can vary some. So I put all the spices in the grinder, including the dry Rosemary & Thyme. (No fresh remember) Used an extra tablespoon or two of Olive oil to make a paste. (the extra dry spices soaked up the first tblsp of oil) Spread the paste on a room tempature roast, let it rest for an hour then followed the rest of the direction. WOW - WOW - WOW Don't know how the original could be any better.

Rating: 4
I had a 16.5 lb prime rib roast to cook for Christmas. This recipe is excellent. I basically trippled the recipe and went for it. I did not use bay leaves, salt, or thyme. I used fresh basil and a quantity of olive oil to form the paste. I also placed slices of garlic, 4 per rib section as another chef commented about. The big decision was how long to cook the roast being it was 16.5 lbs. Since it was cylindrical in nature, I was of the opinion that the weight did not make a difference. A roast is the same cicular size regardless of the weight. Therefore, the 110 deg provided for a medium rare roast throughout, with the ends and exterior one inch being medium well. It was very juicy and provided a very exciting dinner.

