Rating: 4
This was a big hit on Christmas Day! It was so tender that most of our guests didn't even need the jus. We cooked it a lot longer than the recipe required... until our instant-read thermometer read 125 degrees. Then it continued to cook on the counter for the next 25 minutes before carving to the perfect temperature- approximately 140 degrees. I'm very glad that we let it cook longer. Taking it out at 110 degrees (as the recipe says) would have resulted in an extremely rare roast.

Rating: 4
I used this recipe for a 14 lb. 7 rib crown roast. I doubled the recipe for the herbed paste, added a little more olive oil, about a tablespoon of worcestershire, and about a teaspoon of cumin, and let it marinate overnight. Using the crown roast, I put the paste on the cut portions of the roast. My only concern was how long to roast, as I didn't want it to be overdone. As it turned out I undercooked it and it was rare, but mostly everyone wanted it that way, and it was sooooo tender. For the one person who wanted their's cooked more, we put their portion back in the oven. It was really delicious!

Rating: 4
